Administration, Faculty and Students
Have No Communication, wilson Says
To the Editor:
Cultural and intellectual life
has sponsored this year at
Grinnell. Classes, guest lectures, dramatic productions,
and concerts have all been
stimulating. There is an active
group social life; adult lead<
ership still generally displays
a moderate attitude toward our
affairs. Yet there is a your note
in the symphony. Something is
wrong.
Students are discussed or
placed on promotion with start
explanation. When a protest is
made at the increasing stringency of discipline, those in
authority reply, “Pretty soon
we start shooting people down."
The word gets out that if one
is “heat.” he had better before. Faculty, parents, and
alumni are reported to be trying more statement control, The
reader may say that this is
merely a mood in the air, un—
defined and hourly supported.
Yet this is the key to the problem. If some among us have
specific proposals to make, can
they not identify themselves
and speak out publicly, so their
ideas may be saturday and
reasonably discussed? This
open approach might be highly
construction and certainly less
confusion.
Admittedly, we as students
must take responsibility for
our many mistakes. I do not
believe we are committed to a
burdensome and realistic interpretation of all social rules,
 
but I know we are dedicated to
serve the end of those codes—
building a happy association
where relevant people respect
each other. ,
Where we have failed, our
freedoms have been lost. The
emergency in Langan Hall il
an example. We all must recall,
however, that student initiatives have not only been A
lifetime part of our way of life,
but may be found in the earliest
Western universities of the Middle Ages. The arbitrary authority of administrations is n
more recent innovation. in reporting our government
through the coming references, we will be continuing a
process which is no new had.
but is in various forms the
heritage of centuries.
The solution to our misunderstanding lies in the very
nature of the Grinnell experiment. We have grown by a
free use of reason and a relevant social miller. We will stagnate by the nostalgic opposition of stories middle class mobility. extensions, suggestions,
and promotions will miss the
mark. The youthful, operated,
and anticipated character of
Grinnell student society would
be quickly lost if its liberal
essence were removed. Open
dialogue on policy with certain
respect for our rights is essential for us to work harmoniously and creativity with the administration.
David wilson
 
