Couririghi: Village Builds ‘New Sense of signing'
Ed. Note: This is the second and final part of a report
from Paul Courtright, ’64,
who is serving as a Grinnell
Travel-Service Scholar at Ahmednagar College in India
this year.
In the village itself, new homes
are being constructed of steady
rock, relatively specials and having windows, replacing the haphazard, wilderness structures of
prostores cow lung and grass
rooms, filled with smoke from the
family cooking fire.
The labor is provided by the village people themselves, some ma-
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
is losing out because of this trend?"
“1 don't mind so much that our
young are leaving the villages. I
know that these boys who are going to colleges and later sterling
in the cities will use their education to help us, either directly as
Government officers, or indirectly
in business or professional work
These young men who bizrate to
the city in search of jobs many
times have left their wives and
children, or brothers and sisters
behind and send money home to
support them. Our family ties are
very deep; they will not forget us”
One of the women brought some
tea. Indian tea is a mixture of
as '
AN INDIAN WOMAN hands a pan oi travel to a
act—worker on the Kolhewadi Road project'.
rentals such as sheet metal looking
is supplied by the government. By
this kind of activity, the village
people with their new houses put
together a new sense of density.
I talked with the until of the Vilv
logo of Kolhewadiu His name is
Bapuji changes Shelke, a man of
about 4550, a Maratha by waste,
and farmer by profession. The
lines in his face, his long mustache, beginning or grey at the
edges, his white turban manually tied on his head and having a
slight coat of red dust from the
fields, all showed him to be a man
used to hard work and concerned
about the settlement of the people
of his village. As he sat on his
launches against the wall of an
ancient Hindu temple in honor of
Lord china where we had located
the hot afternoon sun, he lit up a
cigarette and failed. His teeth
showed the red states of showing
‘pan,’ or connection of spaces and
hotel nut which leaves a mild narcotic effect.
First I asked him, "DO you be
leave the Government is trying to
improve your way of life?" He
thought for a moment, took are
other drag on his cigarette, and
answered, "I think the Government is there to help our villages
to increase production and raise
the living standard. Sometimes we
are disturbed when we hear of corruption and waste. Certainly some
of the rural development officers
are more interested in drawing
their salary and financing themselves than in helping us to improve things here. But generally I
believe the people in Delhi and the
local executives are trying to help
us. These things take time."
Then i asked, “Many young men
are leaving the villages to attend
college and later sterling in the
cities. Others move to urban areas
in search of more charitable employment. Do you think the Village
 
strong tea with milk and sugar
joined together. He posted the tea
into the cancer and financing it on
his finger tips, blowing on the
surface of the liquid to cool it,
fucked it noisily into his mouth
and swallowed.
“What do you think about the
population 'explosion’ in India today?"
“I am not worried about population extensions To my mind, me
most urgent problem is increasing
food production. When we can
raise our yield by better farming
methods and irrigation, then we
can feed and support many more
people, even than we have now.
All this talk about family planning
is not the answer. What we must
do is grow more food and im»
prove our land.”
in a couple of more months the
road connecting Kolhewadi with
the main road will be finished. The
vibrators have worked long hours
in the hot sun, earning 30c per
day during this black season while
they wait for the harvest of their
trains. These are hard times. The
food prices because of showtimes
have given 100% in three years. To
those people on consistency becomes, the pressure is intense. By
building the road they can earn
enough money to carry on until
harvest. The students have donated their labor as a feature of
faith in the villages growth.
The story of Koihewadi is not a
dramatic one, belt it is typical
enough of the job that has to be
done. No crash program from Delhi
can bring rural India out of its
backwardness. It Will be a slow
process, a village by village away»
using. it will take a great many
people willing to work at this
level, where there is no glory to be
gained.
And what does the experience at
Kolhewadi say about indian high
er education?
One of the many institutions india inherited from the British was
their educational systems The organization of education in India today is still primarily dramatically
and automatically oriented. The
curriculum. textbooks, selling, and
examinations are prescribed by a
committee of the university to
which a particular college is af—
finished. The individual professor
is alleged to follow these require
meets and prepare the student to
pass the midwest and final ex«
operations which Will determine
his academic standing with the
university.
The advantage of this system is,
of course, university. What is
taught and required across the
country is standardized. But this
university is purchased at a high
price. There is little imagination,
creativity, and resourcefulness re
quoted on the part or the processors
and less from the students. Research work, individual inquiry on
classified topics and intellectual
authority is rare.
The development of the Indian
economy requires minds and
based on sound intellectual thinking and personal experience in
specific situations. The Rural Life
Development and Research Project of Ahmendnagar College is attempting to bring these two never»
cities together for its students.
If a student is studying the organization and management of
rural corporations, he can work
with a cooperative being formed
among several villages for the
processing and marketing of planet oil. If another student is working on the dynamics of conflict between traditional and progressive
elements in village India, he can
take a nearby tribal village in the
first of decision economic and so—
dial change as a case study.
Page F' o
It is this activity of applying economics and sociology into an actual
situation involving real people,
their limitations, corporations, processes and failures, which makes
the Rural Life Project work stimulating.
This article has been an attempt
to give a climate into one small
faces of an Indian experience of the
phenomenon known as “economic
development." There are no
graphs, no statistics, no grand congratulations instead there are people whose lives are being changed,
people who are trying to adjust
from an ancient way of life to n
more prosperous, and inevitably
more undertake one.
 
 
